  "duration": 182.916005888,
  "text": " No single person is strong enough or smart enough to lead by themselves. And so the opportunity isn't to beat yourself up, but to understand what your strengths are and what you bring to the game, and then find people who have strengths that are different to yours. And if you work together, and that's why we have teams. If we were good at everything, we wouldn't need the team. We just need ourselves. I think it also highlights the importance of being too involved in your own company so that you aren't looking for mentors outside of your own company. who are thinking about... Outside your industry. Yeah, or outside your industry. Having a board of directors for me has always been wonderful because you get people who they were a former governor or they were a chief medical officer of a big company or they were in consumer marketing. And they deeply care about the cause and happen to care about me, so it's that safety net. Yeah. And it seems like it's an obligation on us as leaders to seek out those mentoring relationships that are outside of work to help create that safety net. You know, and I'm opening a Pandora's box here, but America screwed up lean, right? When the folks from Harvard decided to bring the Toyota way to the United States, one of the biggest mistakes they made was calling it lean because it was never about efficiency. It was about finding better ways of doing things which is sometimes more efficient and leads to efficiency But America we made it about efficiency which means we made it about counting which it never was And there never been a company that has fully successfully implemented lean in the United States by the way Because of that. Yeah, because they think it's a numbers thing and it's not a numbers thing. There are things within the Toyota way. We're not going to call it lean. There are things within the Toyota way that are brilliant. and one of them is the Kaizen, where you take people who know nothing about a particular part of your business and you make them go work in that and solve it for a week or two. And you mix the company up and you let people try new things and you create blended teams. Because what's happening is somebody is bringing a point of view that nobody on that team has. So it's actually about growth and development. Exactly. And so somebody from, you know, HR working on a medical thing, you know they may say well what about this and no one's ever thought about that before and it's not because they're necessarily smarter it's because they have a different perspective which is you're paying me compliments but i just have a different perspective um and this is the value of of a team because you know and this is one of the challenges in big companies in small companies everybody does everything in big companies we become you know titanium silos of excellence and uh we're closed to what other people have to say because they don't understand, as opposed to being curious about what other people have to say. And I loved what you said before. It's not no because, it's yes if.",
